This is the multi-script flow of my program

Langchain Enhancement_v04/
│
├── config.py       ← constants and model instance
├── schemas.py      ← Pydantic models and parsers
├── prompts.py      ← PromptTemplate definitions
├── chains.py       ← chain assembly (prompt | model | parser)
├── evaluation.py   ← EVAL_DATASET and evaluate_chain()
└── main.py         ← orchestrator: runs eval, then runs analysis


Each file, its contents, and the reason for the boundary
• config.py — the single source of truth for settings
    Why isolate this? Because these are the values you'll change most often when experimenting —
    swapping phi3:mini for llama3, adjusting temperature, trying a different seed. With this file,
    you change one value in one place and every other file that imports it gets the update automatically.
    Without it, you'd be hunting for hardcoded strings scattered across four files.
• schemas.py — data structure definitions
    Why isolate this? Your schemas define what data looks like — that's a separate concern from what the model does
    with it or how prompts are structured. If you later add a fourth output class, you touch only this file.
• prompts.py — prompt construction
    Notice the import line: from schemas import intent_parser, .... This file depends on schemas.py.
    That dependency is explicit and visible at the top of the file — which is the point.
• chains.py — assembly only
    This file does exactly one thing: wire components together into chains. It doesn't define what a chain does,
    it doesn't define what the model is — it only connects pieces that are defined elsewhere.
• evaluation.py — evaluation logic
• main.py — the orchestrator, nothing else
    One thing you haven't seen before: `if __name__ == "__main__"`
    This guard appears in `main.py` and you'll see it everywhere. Here's what it does.
    When Python imports a file, it executes it. That means if `main.py` had `progressive_intent_analysis(sample_text)`
        at the top level with no guard, importing it from another script would **immediately run your analysis** —
        which you never wanted.
    `__name__` is a built-in variable Python sets automatically.
    When a file is run directly (`python main.py`), `__name__` equals `"__main__"`. When a file is imported by another file,
        `__name__` equals the filename instead. The guard means: *only run this block if this file is the entry point,
        not if it's being imported*.
    Every file that has execution logic at the bottom should have this guard.
    Your other files (`schemas.py`, `config.py`, etc.) don't need it because they only define things —
        they don't execute anything when imported.


One last thing to internalise. Read the imports in each file and you get a strict hierarchy — data flows in one direction only:

config.py       ← no dependencies
schemas.py      ← no dependencies
    ↑
prompts.py      ← depends on schemas
    ↑
chains.py       ← depends on config, schemas, prompts
    ↑
evaluation.py   ← depends on config
    ↑
main.py         ← depends on chains, evaluation

Nothing in this diagram points backward. config.py does not import from main.py. schemas.py does not know that chains exist.
This one-directional flow is what makes the architecture maintainable — you can read, modify, or test any layer without understanding everything above it.